Given that it is the most expensive of the mobile Kingdom Rush series I found it the most disappointing, too. At start we can switch between 2 heroes, Eridan (archer) & Arrivan (mage), which is decent enough, as pay-to-play heroes & heroines COULD be purchased. But the overall graphics is not ... It is more crude than expected. Technically install was flawless, and it runs on my chromebook without any problems. Map by map it just looks, as if some more care for optics would have been fun (personal touchscreen issues excluded, they stem from my hardware settings). With trademark being no issue: I found the Ewoks pretty cool, but fantasy is not lightsabres, and we cannot choose Jedi or Sith either (mission 4 or 5 it was). Tactically this game is already tough on medium difficulty, which will make some players very happy. Plus: Many maps have something to click, animated figures with humorous lil surprises, so the easily bored may not freak-out. Sorry, after Kingdom Rush Frontiers I had higher expectations, not a mere repeat of the known concept with pointy ears & lots of green-brown coloring...

Ever since Kingdom Rush 1, this has been the original and best BY FAR of 
all the defence games out there. I see many games trying to copy the 
gameplay and graphics claiming originality, but this company has been the 
first, and tops. I respect them and will continue to support them fully. 
They are not money sucking, and they stick to the basics which is so hard 
to find nowadays. Also the Easter eggs found in Origins are so memorable! 
Lord of the Rings, Batman, etc: so many that if you're not looking or 
listening, you won't find them. But it's an fun appreciation they have for 
their fans. Keep doing what you guys are doing and continue making these 
game! Much love.

Origins is a pretty solid game with nice graphics, audio, and strategy. I 
have only one problem with it - the heroes are all weird. Many of them have 
no relation to the games lore and are completely unremarkable to normal 
people. When I think about heroes I don't think about pixies, ice-men, 
ninja pandas, and phoenixes, I think about paladins, crusaders, rogues, and 
more simple, classical things. I get that they don't just want to reuse 
tired archetypes, but doing something so radically different risks losing 
some people's interest.

love the art style and game mechanics and scenario design. The game is just 
complex enough to keep you interested, but not so complex as to be

game. Watching ads is optional for really helpful in-game currency, and 
that is the best!

First off, this is an amazing tower defence game. If you've played the previous games in the series you will definitely want this. It expands on gameplay to give more variety to levels and heroes (who now have unique spells attached to them).   I do love the writing (although I do wish there was more of it) and the art style is gorgeous.  My only real gripe with this game is that, despite being a premium game with an upfront cost, you still don't actually get access to the full game. While you do get all the levels, most of the heroes are locked behind a paywall, with a total cost of around ¬£40 for all of them... I love your games Ironhide but I'm not spending 10 times the original price for more content.  Now the game is definitely fun despite the microtransactions, but I would prefer if they weren't there. Or if Ironhide tweaked the DLC so it was worth the price (say, a set of levels themed around the purchased hero maybe, because more levels at the rest of the game's quality would be amazing) I would have given this 4/5 stars. But for now it's 4/5. Good game, but bad microtransaction choice.

Origins is honestly a step back from Kingdom Rush: Frontiers. There are less tower placements slots in levels compared to previous Rush titles, probably to intentionally make the game harder. If you're a Kingdom Rush fan you will like this game, just don't expect anything original or anything above Frontiers. That said, this is still one of the better tower defense games available for mobile.

This game is not pay to win or even pay to enhance your gaming experience, you can have just as much fun with the free to play heroes. The game has surprising depth which will surprise first timers and at higher difficulty levels even challenge veterans of the genre. Definitely recommend this game to someone looking to play a light hearted take on a fantasy tower defense game with enough of a challenge to keep you interested for quite some time.

Overall excellent. Not 5 stars because‚Äã some level designs are needlessly complex. It's not interesting to have to memorize and/or track which teleporters go where. The interesting parts are planning out tower placement, using resources effectively, and managing heroes/abilities.  Also, some levels introduce new enemies literally on the first wave giving you no way to know how to plan around them. This leads often to restarting right away and needing to completely redo your tower placements all over again, which is time consuming.

Truly a great experience. This game has an extremely cliched and formulaic but servicable story, which is more than enough for it. The aspects of the game that really shine is the great variety and fun gameplay. The "fun" part is entirely subjective, really, but variety is truly worth mentioning. You can use whatever tower you want, none of them are too underpowered. There are so many different enemy types and bosses, and heroes. It never feels repetitive. One of the most cost efficent games I've ever seen. The amount of content for the price you pay is unbelievable. 5/5 Definitely recommended if you like the tower defense genre. Though I would recommend playing the free Kingdom Rush game first if you want to get into the genre.

I played the other Kingdom Rushes on my iPad and even bought more heroes to support the developer since I loved playing these games so much. Was very excited to play this one on my new Dell Venue 10 7000 android tablet. However, as I was progressing in the game I noticed one day the game would not load. I would initiate the game only to have it flash black and crash. I tried all I could to troubleshoot (reboot the device, research google), but the only way to fix it was uninstalling and reinstalling, and I knew doing so would delete my progress. And I was right. I didn't play the game for over a week cause I didn't want to restart.  Because I really enjoy this game, I decided to start over. However this time around I logged into my Google account hoping that maybe it saves progression in the cloud. Eventually got further than I originally did before I experienced problems. But just today I experienced the same issue. Was forced to reinstall again which again deleted my save. Hoped logging into Google would restore my save, but didn't.  To summarize, I will no longer play this game or any other game from this dev until they fix the crash issue AND implement cloud progress saving.

replyContent: Hi there! The only purchasable extra content are the Heroes, all the maps are available. Also, we are currently working on Cloud Sync for Android. Thank you.

I absolutely adore the Kingdom Rush games. I even recommended them to a few of my friends. The 'In-App Purchases' absolutely ruin the game though. I picked up a couple of these games on Steam and in Humble Bundles where you get all the content and I played for hours. I absolutely refuse to spend a penny on unlocking individual parts of the game though. I will pay full price from the beginning, but refuse to be nickel-and-dimed to death when I'm actually playing the game. All that being said, I enjoy the way the games have changed over time. In one of them your heroes levelled up to their max level during each level that you played, while in another your levels were persistent. It might be nice to have the option to choose which way you want to play the game. I find that the one method (levelling up every level) encouraged me to try different heroes and really opened up my love for some that I hadn't previously tried. The other method (persistent levels) really let you maximize the powers of your favourite heroes. Even if you lost you would still at least gain something out of the time you spent playing. The only problem is that this method discouraged trying out low levelled heroes

With that said, some things are still missing like cloud saves and immersive mode. Overall, one of the best, if not the best TD game.

Excellent and challenging, like the previous two incarnations. And it's not just a rehash of the old, this one has new tricks up its sleeves (w/o spoiling too much, it's about enemies' paths). I'm deducting one star because if you want to unlock all heroes, it will set you back $114.41 (not because there are many heroes to unlock, but because they're expensive). That's the price of not one, but two AAA titles. And the game only comes with three heroes. Also a nasty aspect is that on a mobile device you have to scroll. This makes it all too easy for a critter to slip by your defenses. And in challenge modes, one critter is all it takes. The developers did all they could to work around this (it's not their fault mobile screens are small) and there's a warning that shows up when you have scrolled away and something gets past your defenses, but by the time you scroll back it's usually too late to do anything about it. I'm not deducting any stars for this. Fwiw, it works just fine on a lowly Moto G, I have no idea why some reviews are complaining about the game's lack of optimization.

If you've played any of the earlier games in the series then this is "more of the same",  this being a prequel.  For those who haven't  played an earlier title,  then you're missing out on a real treat. Graphics are lush, sounds are spot-on,  gameplay excellent,  with abundant amounts of humorous "easter eggs" in the levels. Only downside is that one you've finished on "veteran" level there's no real incentive to play again. I'd be more than happy to pay for extra level packs. As it is,  the in-app is limited to new playable characters, which don't add that much to the gameplay. With the possibility of extra levels to extend playtime this would be a dead cert for 5*, as it is though it's 4.5. Tip:don't try and play on a phone,  this really needs a tablet screen to appreciate properly!

Was looking forward to this game as I loved the previous in the series. Missions are fun, varied and require some thinking. However difficulty is much much lower than previous games and I never needed more than 2/3 tries to complete a mission on 3*s. I never even used the (much more expensive) gnome shop. Towers also felt much weaker: mage towers especially. No bonus extra-hard missions after completing the game was was very disappointing as its what kept me playing (struggling) the previous games much longer than the main missions.  In terms of heroes, I really liked them, especially the wizard - my favorite by far. However there were only 4, which is much less than Frontiers, which was much less than Kingdoms with another ~8 PAID heroes which I find ridiculous in a full price game - and annoyed me in Frontiers. Also still not being able to play my own music and play the game is just stupid.  In conclusion, Origins is a much weaker game than Frontiers. And I'd recommend buying that one over this. This game feels more like a freemium game, what with the fewer missions, fewer heroes. Disappointed.

This is a fun installment to the Kingdom Rush series, but is definitely NOT worth the money.  Do yourself a favor and buy the original or Frontiers.  You get far more content.  The biggest complaint is that there is no replayability.  Once the campaign has been beaten, no bonus levels are unlocked and no endless mode is available.  Second complaint, IAP. I'd rather not purchase a game and then find out that there are $25 more in IAP that are required to unlock the FULL game.  Seems sneaky.  Make a free version, or a full version... not a mix of both.

The mage towers are now multi-shot towers for a start which adds a new strategy beyond just being anti-armour towers, and the hero now provides a special spell that can be improved along with their progression.
